The Mandela Effect is actually named for a shared misconception about Nelson Mandela’s death. There were a lot of people who had a very strong memory of seeing news reports about him dying in his prison cell—including the person who coined the term. 

It’s become a term for any kind of common false memory, often one that is so ingrained people are shocked to learn it’s wrong (if they even believe that). So the Johnny Winter example you gave would also be Mandela Effect, assuming those fans remembered witnessing official reports that they actually hadn’t. Otherwise, it’s just a rumor. 😉

